\section{Introduction}     
\subsection{Reasons to Study Data Science}
\subsubsection{Conduct Research}

The first reason is to administer a  research projects. Without  statistics you will have tough time making decisions based on the data that you collected for your research project. Statistics provides you with  tools to make an informed decision. You will be able to decide which of the possibilities is more likely to be true. You will base this decision on your knowledge of  inferential statistics and probability. 

\subsubsection{Study Design}

The second reason to study statistics is that you are equipped to read scientific journals. Most technical journals that you will read contain some form of statistics. Usually, you will find them in the results section of the report. If you are not familiar with statistics, the information contained in this section will be meaningless.  An understanding of introductory statistics will provide you with the fundamental skills necessary to read and evaluate most results sections. The ability to extract meaning from journal articles and the ability to critically evaluate research from a statistical perspective are fundamental skills that will enhance your knowledge and understanding in related programs of study. 

\subsubsection{Develop Critical Thinking Skills}

The third reason is to further develop critical and analytic thinking skills.  After completing high school and introductory undergraduate coursework, you will have at your disposal a variety of critical thinking and analytic skills. The study of statistics will serve to enhance and further develop these skills. By doing well in statistics, you will develop and use formal logical thinking abilities that are both high level and creative. 

\subsubsection{Be an Informed Consumer}

The fourth reason to study statistics is to be an informed consumer. Like any other tool, statistics can be used or abused.  Yes, it is true that some individuals do actively lie and mislead with statistics. More often, however, well meaning individuals unintentionally report erroneous statistical conclusions. If you know some of the basic statistical concepts, you will be in a better position to evaluate the information that you have been given. 

\subsubsection{Know When to Hire a Statistician}

The fifth reason to have a working knowledge of statistics is to know when you need to help from a statistician.  Most of us know enough about our mobile devices to know when to take it into the shop.  Usually, we do not attempt the repair ourselves because we do not want to cause any irreparable damage.  Also, we try to know enough to speak intelligibly with service center employee to insure that we do not get a replacement when we need a replacement cord for our ear buds.   We should be the same way about employing a statistician.  Doing research is expensive in terms of resources and time. If you are in over your statistical head, it does not make sense to risk an entire project by attempting to compute the data analyses yourself.  It is very easy to compute incomplete or inappropriate statistical analysis of our data. As with the service center employee discussed above, it is also important to have enough statistical where with all to be able to discuss your project and the data analyses you want computed with the statistician you hire. In other words, you want to be able to make sure that your statistician is on the right track. 

\subsubsection{To summarize}

The five reasons to study statistics are to be able to effectively conduct research, to be able to read and evaluate journal articles, to further develop critical thinking and analytic skills, to act a an informed consumer, and to know when you need to hire outside statistical help. % \cite{URL}{knoko}

\subsubsection{{Research}} Research  is the systematic inquiry into the study of situations to establish facts and reach new conclusion.

\subsubsection{{Data science}}  Data science is the systemic study of the study of structure and behavior of collecting, organizing, evaluating, and interpreting data.  The interpretation phase refers population characteristics from sampling.

\subsubsection{{Data}} Data are information collected from the population for further analysis.

