\subsubsection{Theory}  Theory is a statement used to explain a situation, eg., does the amount of sleep of  students affect their academic performance.

\subsubsection{Hypothesis}  Hypothesis is an explanation about an association between events, eg.,  the amount of sleep of a student affects the student GPA.

\subsubsection{Observations}  Observations are collected data to test hypothesis, eg., a random sample of student GPA and hours of sleep.

\subsubsection{Empirical Generalizations}  Empirical generalizations are made to assess the theory after analyzing the data, eg., analysis shows a relationship between amount of sleep of a student and GPA. 


\subsubsection{Variables and Cases}

\subsubsection{Variables}

\begin{itemize}
\item Theories and hypotheses are asserting the association between variables.
\item A theory may identify some variables as causes (independent variables) and others as effects or results (dependent variable).
\item Variables are attributes of a case.
\item Examples: age, gender, race, and social class.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Case}

\begin{itemize}
\item Case is a collection of variables from an entity such as a person.
\item Cases are gathered from groups.
\item Examples: groups (e.g., church members, union members), people, city, and states.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Example}

Illustrate the color of eyes of students in this class.

\begin{itemize}
\item Variable is color of eyes of students
\item Data is color such as black, blue, brown, green, hazel.
\item Cases are students from this class.
\item Appropriate analysis include:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item frequency (number) of students who have brown eyes.
	\item percent of students who have blue eyes.
	\item bar chart showing the percentage of each color of eyes.
	\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}	
     
\section{Types of Statistics}


\subsection{Descriptive Statistics}

Descriptive statistics are use to explain the basic features of the data in a study.

There are three methods of describing data.

\begin{enumerate}
\item {\bf{Univariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{one variable at a time}}, such as averages, percentages, charts and graphs:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The average IQ of the class is 120
	\item The percent of females taking Stat 2830 this semester is 55 percent.
	\end{itemize}
\item {\bf{Bivariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{two variables at a time}}, such as 
looking for relationships between two variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item The relationship between GPA and age is positive and strong.
	\item The relationship between gender and shopping is negative and moderate.
	\end{itemize}	
\item {\bf{Multivariate}} descriptive statistics -- summarizes {\bf{three or more variables at a time}}, such as 
looking for relationships between three or more variables that describe strength and direction.
	\begin{itemize}
	\item Generally, as GPA increases with age for females but not for males.
	\end{itemize}	
\end{enumerate}


\subsection{Inferential Statistics}

Inferential statistics makes a general statement about a population from a sample of the population.

