\begin{itemize}
\item Population (P) contains all cases.  Usually, it is very large which makes a complete enumeration of all values nearly impossible because of budget limitations.
\item Samples (S) are part of the population.  While, a sample represents a part of the population which is a manageable size.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Inferential Statistics Example}

Since 1968, voter surveys use inferential statistics.

\begin{itemize}
\item A random sample of voters are polled about their voting preferences.
\item The results are used to estimate the voting preferences of all voters.
\item e.g., The Democrat candidate will receive about 48 percent of the vote in Kalamazoo County.
\end{itemize}

\section{Types of Data}
\subsection{Categorical (qualitative data)}

\begin{itemize}
\item characteristics CANNOT be measured.
\item e.g., gender, eye color, race, political affiliation, social status, etc.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Levels of Measurement for Categorical Data}

\begin{itemize}
\item Nominal categorical variable has no order:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item e.g., The scores are labels and ordering does not exist.
	\item e.g., gender, SSN, the names of food pantries in Kalamazoo County.
	\end{itemize} 
\item Ordinal categorical variable has order:
	\begin{itemize}
	\item e.g., The scores can be ranked and ordering does exist.
	\item e.g., The management structure of at city hall, class levels, rating scales.
	\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
		

\subsection{Numerical (quantitative data)}

\begin{itemize}
\item characteristics CAN be measured.
\item e.g., age, height, weight, number of students in this class, etc.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Levels of Measurement for Numerical Data}

\begin{itemize}
\item An interval numerical  variable has magnitude but the ratio is not allowed
	\begin{itemize}
	\item e.g., GPA, IQ, temperature, 
	\item e.g., 60 degrees is not twice as warm as 30 degrees.
	\end{itemize} 
\item A ratio numerical variable has a meaningful zero value, a proportion is allowed, and has magnitude.
	
		\begin{itemize}
		\item {\bf{Discrete}}
		\item result of a counting process (whole number values)
		\item results of question ``how many?''
		\item e.g., number of children per family.
		
		\item {\bf{Continuous}}
		
		\item has scores that can be subdivided infinitely (at least theoretically)
		\item e.g., age, income, distance to school.
		\end{itemize}
	
	
\end{itemize}

